Ciphers are infiltration and intelligence practitioners whose tradition crystallized in the breakdown of the charter road network after the Ninth Meridian Catastrophe. Three lineages converged: route guides (former Keeper Era road wardens who sold knowledge of pre-collapse route networks and secondary paths), fence operators (merchants from the charter system's shadow economy who continued moving undocumented goods through post-collapse authority gaps), and private intelligence dealers (former Jackal Synod scribes and document processors whose skills in forgery, seal duplication, and record manipulation found new markets). All three lineages share the foundational insight that institutional control creates its own bypass architecture: any system comprehensive enough to regulate activity produces seams its own rules cannot cover. The tradition was never written down because writing was what legitimate institutions did, and legitimacy was what the collapse had temporarily made unavailable. Knowledge transmits through oral apprenticeship outside institutional frameworks. Three moral positions coexist within the tradition: the Pragmatist (gaps are properties of rule systems, not moral failures), the Reform (demonstrating where control systems are inadequate is a social service), and the Transactional (moral status is determined case by case by who benefits and who is harmed). Cipher practitioners advance into Warlock or Assassin remort paths depending on which skill set they deepen. The Nightblade synthesis combines both successor paths.

